{"body":"@smpa01 You are not alone in these results. (See also [this Interspeech 2024 paper](https://www.isca-archive.org/interspeech_2024/rousso24_interspeech.html).) Perhaps you can preserve the VAD & batch whisper processing of WhisperX but use MFA for the alignment. This somewhat answers the question posed here: https://github.com/m-bain/whisperX/issues/461","created_at":"2025-10-06T16:59:38Z","user":"erklem"}
{"body":"You could also experiment with [CrisperWhisper](https://github.com/nyrahealth/CrisperWhisper)","created_at":"2025-10-06T18:11:39Z","user":"erklem"}
{"body":"I can confirm that WhisperX alignment seems to be way off. What I seeing (hearing :)) on my end are timestamps starting in the middle of the first word of sentences. In a particular case, the sentence starts after a long period of silence, and timestamp is still way off. We can clearly see how much it is off by loading the audio on Audacity (or whatever.)

I tried different models and also playing with VAD options, like loweing the `vad-onset` value, but it didn't help. 

edit: tested Montreal-Forced-Aligner
The good: MFA did a much better job on the problematic sentences. 

The bad: unfortunately MFA comes with its own set of problems.
-  Installing it without conda requires a priest, 10 Buddhists monks, and sacrificing 20 virgins.
- one of my problematic sentences started with `1. Avocado banana`. MFA gave the `1.` a very precise timestamp, but replaced the text with `<unk>`. At first I thought it didn't support numerals, but another similar sentence started with `10. Carrot death` and this time it had no problem with the `10.` ","created_at":"2025-10-15T15:07:06Z","user":"to-audiobook"}
{"body":"I've been facing the same problems. Decided to give `gentle` a try and it performed extremely well. 

Just like `MFA`, sometimes it does not understand a word and replaces it by `<unk>`. Unlike `MFA`, `gentle` gives you the original word too, so you can just use that and ignore the `<unk>`

The biggest problem with `gentle` is that it also relies on `kaldi`, which is not a package most distros carry. It is not that hard to build it, and `gentle` comes with a `install.sh` script that will do it all for you. But the script needs some light-patching to work and building kaldi, even if you patch the script to build only what is really required, takes a quite a while.

The good news is that a static build (with CUDA enabled, O3, march and mtune native,  omit-frame-pointer and no debug info) can be compressed to 15MB. I think LTO might makes things even better, but I forgot to enable it.

I'm thinking maybe we could add a new option to use a different aligner and leave it to the user to pass a path to the required binaries.","created_at":"2025-10-23T21:37:31Z","user":"libTorrentUser"}
